abstract: Rupert Goold’s film adaptation of a book by the discredited journalist Michael Finkel focuses on his wary friendship with a man charged with murder who had impersonated him.
snippet: Rupert Goold’s film adaptation of a book by the discredited journalist Michael Finkel focuses on his wary friendship with a man charged with murder who had impersonated him.
lead_paragraph: “The Journalist and the Murderer” is the title of a book by Janet Malcolm, but it could just as well be the name of a genre. A small library of searching and sensational stories attests to the strong, often uncomfortable affinity between reporters and killers. Truman Capote’s “In Cold Blood” is perhaps the supreme example, and one that has inspired several movies over the years. Neither Michael Finkel’s book “True Story” nor Rupert Goold’s film adaptation is anywhere near as accomplished as Capote’s book or Bennett Miller’s movie “Capote.” The new film is of interest mainly because it demonstrates just how difficult it can be to map the queasy moral territory where crime and journalism intersect.

headline_print_headline: Fact and Fiction Collide in a Tale of Journalism and Crime

abstract: I ran out of interest in my own consciousness around 1990, but there’s no reason ever to run out of interest in the world.
snippet: I ran out of interest in my own consciousness around 1990, but there’s no reason ever to run out of interest in the world.
lead_paragraph: When I was in graduate school at Johns Hopkins in the early 1980s, I played on the intramural softball team of the postmodern literary theorist Stanley Fish. I recall his umpiring at a practice once when the batter, my buddy Mike, now a distinguished professor at Yale, argued a call. Fish good-humoredly pointed out that what’s a ball and what’s a strike is not an objective, external, or natural fact, it’s an interpretive practice; and according to that practice, whatever the umpire calls is real: If he calls it a strike, it’s a strike. (So that was a strike, Mike.)

headline_main: Philosophy Returns to the Real World

abstract: Michael T. Slager was just a small-town police officer, but a shooting on April 4 has made him a symbol of law enforcement gone awry.
snippet: Michael T. Slager was just a small-town police officer, but a shooting on April 4 has made him a symbol of law enforcement gone awry.
lead_paragraph: NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. — Michael T. Slager played cops and robbers as a boy in the Virginia woods, volunteered as an emergency medical technician after high school and earned an associate degree in criminal justice while working full time as a patrolman.

abstract: When a man approached Walter Scott’s family with the video, what might have been another shooting of a black man by the police suddenly became an astonishing glimpse of life and death.
snippet: When a man approached Walter Scott’s family with the video, what might have been another shooting of a black man by the police suddenly became an astonishing glimpse of life and death.
lead_paragraph: NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. — It was at a vigil Sunday for his slain brother that Anthony Scott found out what he had believed was true all along.

abstract: The North Charleston officer, who is white, had said Mr. Scott, an apparently unarmed black man, took his stun gun. But a video shows the officer firing at him eight times.
snippet: The North Charleston officer, who is white, had said Mr. Scott, an apparently unarmed black man, took his stun gun. But a video shows the officer firing at him eight times.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A white police officer in North Charleston, S.C., was charged with murder on Tuesday after a video surfaced showing him shooting in the back and killing an apparently unarmed black man while the man ran away.

abstract: The singer, who made a comeback in New York clubs after retiring from musical acting to raise her sons, was 90.
snippet: The singer, who made a comeback in New York clubs after retiring from musical acting to raise her sons, was 90.
lead_paragraph: Julie Wilson, the revered nightclub performer and actress widely regarded as the queen of cabaret, died on Sunday in Manhattan. She was 90.

headline_main: Julie Wilson, Sultry Cabaret Legend and Actress, Dies at 90
headline_print_headline: Julie Wilson, Cabaret Legend, Dies at 90

abstract: “A Chorus Line,” the 1975 musical about the trials of auditioning, is being performed with high energy at the John W. Engeman Theater.
snippet: “A Chorus Line,” the 1975 musical about the trials of auditioning, is being performed with high energy at the John W. Engeman Theater.
lead_paragraph: “Everything was beautiful at the ballet” is one of the most recognizable song lyrics from “A Chorus Line.” A similar line, “Everything is beautiful at the theater,” could be the overall theme of the 1975 musical, which won nine Tony Awards and a Pulitzer Prize in 1976. For the characters in this show about show business, no matter the ups and often painful downs of auditioning, they are never sure they will get a job or, if they do, how long it will last.

abstract: An Indiana law has become a thorn for Republicans, especially in their dealings with business leaders.
snippet: An Indiana law has become a thorn for Republicans, especially in their dealings with business leaders.
lead_paragraph: Good Thursday morning from Washington, where Senator Robert Menendez’s corruption charges are already becoming a political problem for Democrats. President Obama is heading to Kentucky to talk about the economy, while Speaker John A. Boehner wraps up his big international trip. Jeb Bush seems to have modified his response to an Indiana law seen as both a protection of religious freedom and an invitation for discrimination, while the law has become a thorn for Republicans, especially in their dealings with business leaders.
